{"slug": "pyromancy", "root": "pyromancy", "category": "divination", "gloss": "divination by fire", "definition": "Pyromancy is divination by fire — reading the future in flame, its color, its crackle, and the shapes it throws. One of a long roster of named mantic arts, it takes its place beside geomancy (earth), hydromancy (water), and aeromancy (air) in the classical scheme that sorts prophecy by its element.", "history": "The name pairs Greek *pyr*, 'fire', with *manteia*, 'divination' — the same suffix-machine that mass-produces the mantic arts. Fire, alive and unpredictable, made an old oracle, and medieval and Renaissance writers routinely listed pyromancy among the technical forms of divination — geomancy, hydromancy, pyromancy, aeromancy — condemned by the casuists (Clark, *Thinking with Demons*); Pico swept it up among the 'inanities' of superstition (Farmer, *Pico's 900 Theses*). MedievalMagicDB classes it a term for divination by fire, recurring in the lists of illicit knowledge — a category whose weight, like its sister arts, came as much from enumeration as from any surviving manual.", "def_sources": [{"label": "MedievalMagicDB, s.v. Pyromancy", "where": "MedievalMagicDB"}, {"label": "Stuart Clark, Thinking with Demons", "where": "Renaissance magic (PDF)", "url": "https://global.oup.com/academic/product/thinking-with-demons-9780198208082", "url_kind": "publisher", "abstract": "Looks at how educated Europeans between the 1400s and 1700s wrote about witches and demons, and argues these ideas were not fringe nonsense but fit logically with how those same thinkers understood nature, religion, history, and politics at the time."}, {"label": "Stephen A. Farmer, Giovanni Pico della Mirandola: Syncretism in the West", "where": "Renaissance magic (PDF)", "url": "https://press.uchicago.edu/ucp/books/book/distributed/S/bo15686255.html", "url_kind": "publisher", "abstract": "This book presents a full translation and study of Pico della Mirandola's famous 900 Theses of 1486, in which the young philosopher tried to show that Christian, Jewish, Islamic, and ancient Greek and Roman ideas about the universe could all be combined into one grand system of thought."}], "commentary": null, "commentary_sources": [], "is_keyword": false, "etymology": {"lang": "Greek", "origin": "Greek pyr 'fire' + manteia 'divination'", "first": "late 14c.", "note": "One of dozens the -mancy suffix generates. Fire, being alive and unpredictable, was among the oldest oracles.", "hook": "The '-mancy' machine: a suffix that mass-produces prophets."}, "essay": null, "sources": ["Etymonline (Douglas Harper)", "Wiktionary", "classical lexica (Lewis & Short, LSJ, Bosworth–Toller)", "Ted's historical-magic DBs (WitchcraftStudiesDB, AgrippaDOP, MedievalMagicDB)"], "stats": {"flavor_total": 14, "oracle_total": 2, "in_flavor_cards": 13, "in_oracle_cards": 2, "name_match_count": 22, "by_variant": {"pyromancer": 9, "pyromancers": 4, "pyromancy": 3}, "first_year": 1999, "colors": {"R": 33, "C": 1, "U": 1}, "by_year": {"1999": 1, "2002": 1, "2008": 2, "2009": 2, "2013": 3, "2014": 1, "2016": 2, "2017": 1, "2018": 5, "2019": 2, "2020": 1, "2021": 1, "2022": 2, "2023": 3, "2024": 7, "2025": 1}}, "cards": [{"id": "71a176ce-cbe7-4cec-a2ca-58abf59ad964", "name": "Pyromancy", "set": "ULG", "set_name": "Urza's Legacy", "released": "1999-02-15", "type_line": "Enchantment", "rarity": "rare", "colors": ["R"], "img_small": "https://cards.scryfall.io/small/front/3/5/35a91a58-cc8b-47a3-8c53-43c32753a00d.jpg?1782720572", "img_normal": "https://cards.scryfall.io/normal/front/3/5/35a91a58-cc8b-47a3-8c53-43c32753a00d.jpg?1782720572", "scryfall_uri": "https://scryfall.com/card/ulg/88/pyromancy?utm_source=api", "local": "img/pyromancy/71a176ce-cbe7-4cec-a2ca-58abf59ad964.jpg"}, {"id": "696ee797-0c32-4bff-8c3d-02d05835b138", "name": "Goblin Pyromancer", "set": "ONS", "set_name": "Onslaught", "released": "2002-10-07", "type_line": "Creature — Goblin Wizard", "rarity": "rare", "colors": ["